   "source": [
    "## 5. Data Cleaning\n",
    "\n",
    "Data cleaning is the process of detecting and correcting (or removing) corrupt, inaccurate, or irrelevant records from a dataset. In the real world, data is almost always dirty. Cleaning it is not optional — it is essential. A model trained on dirty data will give dirty predictions, a principle known as **\"Garbage In, Garbage Out\" (GIGO)**.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 5.1 Checking Missing Values\n",
    "\n",
    "**What are null values?**  \n",
    "A null value (also called missing value, NaN = Not a Number) represents the absence of data at a specific location in the dataset. It is different from zero. Zero means \"the value is zero.\" Null means \"we do not know what this value is.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why do missing values occur?**\n",
    "- Survey respondents skipped a question.\n",
    "- A sensor malfunction during data collection.\n",
    "- Data entry errors.\n",
    "- Merging datasets where not all records exist in both datasets.\n",
    "\n",
    "**How do missing values affect a model?**  \n",
    "Most machine learning algorithms cannot handle null values at all. If you pass a dataset with missing values to scikit-learn's models, they will raise a `ValueError` and refuse to run. Even if they could run, missing values would bias the model because the algorithm would have no information for those records.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happens if we ignore null values?**  \n",
    "In the best case, your model throws an error and you are forced to deal with it. In the worst case (in some libraries or configurations), null values are silently treated as 0, which introduces severe bias."
   ]
  },
