    "### 5.3 Checking and Removing Duplicates\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why are duplicates dangerous?**\n",
    "\n",
    "A duplicate row means the same record appears more than once. In machine learning, if the same customer appears 5 times in the training data and once in the test data, the model has effectively \"memorized\" that specific pattern. This is a form of data leakage that leads to overly optimistic performance estimates.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Effect on model bias:**\n",
    "Duplicates inflate the importance of duplicated records. If 10 specific customers all gave a rating of 5, and each appears 3 times in the training data, the model will overfit to the characteristics of those 10 customers and will not generalize well to new customers.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Real-world example:**\n",
    "In a fraud detection system, if legitimate transactions are duplicated 10 times, the model learns that \"the data is overwhelmingly legitimate\" and will fail to detect rare fraud cases. This is a real problem that has cost financial institutions millions."
