    "## 6. Feature Engineering\n",
    "\n",
    "Feature engineering is the process of creating new, more informative features from existing raw data. It is often described as the most creative and impactful part of data science. A well-engineered feature can dramatically improve model performance, sometimes more than switching to a more powerful algorithm.\n",
    "\n",
    "The intuition behind feature engineering: raw data often contains information in a form that is not directly useful for a model. We transform it into a form that is more meaningful and directly related to the outcome we want to predict.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 6.1 Creating Age from Year of Birth (YOB)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why is Age better than YOB for prediction?**\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider two customers: one born in 1990 and one born in 1970. The YOB values themselves (1990 and 1970) have no direct relationship to rating behavior. But their ages (35 and 55 years old, assuming current year is 2025) are meaningful — older customers may have different taste preferences and rating habits than younger customers.\n",
    "\n",
    "Also, from a model's perspective, the number 1990 is just a large integer. Without context, a model does not inherently understand that 1990 means \"born 35 years ago.\" Age, as a derived feature, is already relative to the current time and directly captures the concept we care about.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happens if we keep YOB directly?**\n",
    "- The model treats YOB as just a raw number. It does not understand the concept of time.\n",
    "- The range of values (1955-2009) may cause scaling issues.\n",
    "- The feature loses temporal meaning as years pass (a model trained in 2023 using YOB would behave differently if deployed in 2030 without retraining).\n",
    "- Age, once derived, is conceptually more stable and directly interpretable."
   ]
