    "## 7. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)\n",
    "\n",
    "Now that our data is clean and properly structured, we begin the core analytical phase. EDA is where we extract meaning from data through visualization and statistical analysis. Every chart we create should answer a specific question.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 7.1 Univariate Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "Univariate analysis examines one variable at a time. The primary goal is to understand the distribution of each feature independently — its shape, central tendency, spread, and the presence of outliers.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What does a distribution tell us?**\n",
    "A distribution shows how frequently each value (or range of values) appears in the data. Understanding distributions helps us:\n",
    "- Know if the data is balanced or imbalanced.\n",
    "- Identify outliers that need attention.\n",
    "- Choose appropriate statistical tests (parametric tests require normally distributed data).\n",
    "- Select appropriate imputation strategies.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What is skewness?**\n",
    "Skewness measures the asymmetry of a distribution. A skewness of 0 means a perfectly symmetric distribution. A positive skewness means the right tail is longer (data is concentrated on the left, with a few very high values). A negative skewness means the left tail is longer.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happens if data is heavily skewed?**\n",
    "Heavy skewness violates the assumptions of linear regression, which assumes normally distributed errors. It can also cause the model to be dominated by extreme values. Common solutions include applying log transformation or square root transformation to reduce skewness."
   ]
  },
