    "### 7.2 Bivariate Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "Bivariate analysis examines the relationship between two variables simultaneously. Instead of asking \"what is the distribution of ratings?\" we now ask \"how does the rating differ between genders?\" or \"which cuisine gets the highest ratings?\"\n",
    "\n",
    "**Correlation vs. Causation:**\n",
    "This is one of the most important distinctions in data science. Correlation means two variables tend to move together. Causation means one variable directly causes a change in the other. The famous example: ice cream sales and drowning rates are correlated (both increase in summer). But ice cream does not cause drowning — heat causes both. Always be careful about inferring causation from correlation in EDA. Bivariate analysis shows correlation; establishing causation requires controlled experiments.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Groupby operations:**\n",
    "`df.groupby('Gender')['Overall Rating'].mean()` splits the data into groups by Gender, then computes the mean rating within each group. This is the fundamental operation for bivariate analysis with one categorical and one numerical variable."
   ]
