    "### 7.3 Multivariate Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "Multivariate analysis examines relationships among three or more variables simultaneously. The most common tool for this is the correlation heatmap.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What is a Correlation Coefficient?**\n",
    "\n",
    "The Pearson correlation coefficient measures the linear relationship between two numerical variables. It ranges from -1 to +1:\n",
    "- **+1:** Perfect positive correlation (as one increases, the other increases proportionally).\n",
    "- **0:** No linear correlation.\n",
    "- **-1:** Perfect negative correlation (as one increases, the other decreases proportionally).\n",
    "\n",
    "In practice, correlations above 0.7 or below -0.7 are considered strong. Between 0.3 and 0.7 (or -0.3 and -0.7) are moderate. Below 0.3 are weak.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What is Multicollinearity?**\n",
    "\n",
    "Multicollinearity occurs when two or more independent features are highly correlated with each other. For example, if `Food Rating` and `Service Rating` are both used to predict `Overall Rating`, and they are highly correlated with each other, the model struggles to determine the individual contribution of each. This causes instability in coefficient estimates in linear regression.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happens if features are highly correlated?**\n",
    "- In Linear Regression: Coefficients become unstable and difficult to interpret. Small changes in training data can cause large changes in coefficients.\n",
    "- In Tree Models: Less of a problem because trees split on individual features independently.\n",
    "- Solution: Remove one of the highly correlated features, use dimensionality reduction (PCA), or use regularization techniques."
   ]
