    "### 7.4 Outlier Detection\n",
    "\n",
    "**What are outliers?**\n",
    "\n",
    "Outliers are data points that are significantly different from the majority of observations. They lie far from the mean, often more than 3 standard deviations away. Outliers can be:\n",
    "- **Genuine outliers:** Real, unusual observations (a customer who rated every restaurant 1 out of spite).\n",
    "- **Error outliers:** Data entry or measurement errors (a budget value of 999 on a 1-5 scale).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Impact of outliers on the mean:**\n",
    "The mean is extremely sensitive to outliers. A single rating of 100 (clearly an error) in a 1-5 dataset would dramatically inflate the mean. The median is not affected because it is determined by position, not value.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Impact on regression models:**\n",
    "Linear regression minimizes the sum of squared errors. Because errors are squared, a single extreme outlier contributes enormously to the loss function, causing the regression line to bend toward it. This results in a model that is fitted to the outlier rather than the general trend.\n",
    "\n",
    "**When to remove outliers and when not to:**\n",
    "- Remove if they are data entry errors (impossible values).\n",
    "- Remove if they are extreme and you are using a sensitive model (linear regression).\n",
    "- Do NOT remove if they represent genuine, important phenomena (in fraud detection, fraudulent transactions ARE the outliers you want to study).\n",
    "- Consider robust models (Random Forest, Huber regression) instead of removing.\n",
    "\n",
    "**The IQR Method:**\n",
    "The Interquartile Range (IQR) is Q3 - Q1. A value is considered an outlier if it is:\n",
    "- Below Q1 - 1.5 * IQR (lower fence)\n",
    "- Above Q3 + 1.5 * IQR (upper fence)"
   ]
