    "### 8.2 Train-Test Split\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why do we split the data?**\n",
    "\n",
    "We split data into a training set and a test set to simulate what happens when the model encounters new, unseen data. The model learns patterns from the training set. Then we evaluate it on the test set, which it has never seen. If it performs well on the test set, we can be confident it has learned genuine patterns, not just memorized the training data.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Overfitting vs. Underfitting:**\n",
    "- **Overfitting:** The model learns the training data too well, including its noise and random fluctuations. It performs excellently on training data but poorly on test data. Think of a student who memorizes every answer in the textbook but cannot solve any new problem.\n",
    "- **Underfitting:** The model is too simple to capture the patterns in the data. It performs poorly on both training and test data. Think of a student who barely studied and cannot answer any question.\n",
    "- **The goal** is the sweet spot: a model that generalizes well — performing well on both training and new data.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Data Leakage:**\n",
    "Data leakage occurs when information from the test set (or from the target variable) \"leaks\" into the training process. This causes the model to appear much better than it actually is. Classic example: if you use `Food Rating` and `Service Rating` to predict `Overall Rating`, and `Overall Rating` is literally computed as the average of these two, you have not built a predictive model — you have just reverse-engineered the formula.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What happens if we train on the full dataset?**\n",
    "Without a test set, we have no way to evaluate how well the model generalizes. We might think the model is excellent when it has simply memorized every training sample, which is useless in production."
   ]
  },
