    "### Model 2: Decision Tree Regressor\n",
    "\n",
    "**How it works mathematically:**\n",
    "\n",
    "A Decision Tree works by recursively partitioning the feature space. At each node, it asks a question: \"Is feature X greater than threshold T?\" Based on the answer, data points are routed to the left or right branch. This continues until leaf nodes are reached, which contain the average rating of all training samples that fell into that region.\n",
    "\n",
    "The splitting criterion for regression trees is typically **mean squared error (MSE)**. At each potential split, the algorithm chooses the feature and threshold that minimize the weighted MSE of the two resulting groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Assumptions:** None of the linear regression assumptions apply. Decision trees are non-parametric.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Strengths:** Can capture non-linear relationships. Requires no feature scaling. Highly interpretable (you can visualize and explain the tree). Handles outliers better than linear regression.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Weaknesses:** Prone to overfitting when the tree is allowed to grow deep (it will essentially memorize training data by creating one leaf per training sample). High variance — small changes in training data can produce very different trees."
   ]
  },
